'''''1000 Forms of Fear''''' is the sixth [[studio album]] by Australian [[singer]] and [[songwriter]] [[Sia (musician)|Sia]], released on 4 July 2014 by Monkey Puzzle and [[RCA Records]] worldwide and [[Inertia (record company)|Inertia Records]] in Australia. Primarily an [[electropop]] album, the record also incorporates influences from [[reggae]] and [[hip hop music|hip hop]]. Lyrically, the record showcases Sia struggling to deal with [[drug addiction]] and [[bipolar disorder]].

''1000 Forms of Fear'' received mostly positive reviews from [[music journalism|music critics]], who praised Sia's vocals as well as the album's lyrical content. The album debuted at number one on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with first-week sales of 52,000 copies. As of January 2015, it has sold 177,000 copies in the United States, according to [[Nielsen SoundScan]]. The release also charted atop the charts of Australia and Canada and reached the top five charts of Denmark, New Zealand, Norway, Sweden and Switzerland.

The album spawned four [[single (music)|singles]]. Its lead single, "[[Chandelier (Sia song)|Chandelier]]", which was released in March 2014, became a worldwide top-ten single. It also peaked at number 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming the first song by Sia to enter the chart as a lead artist. The follow-up singles, "[[Eye of the Needle (song)|Eye of the Needle]]" and "[[Big Girls Cry]]", were released in June 2014. Sia's solo version of "[[Elastic Heart#Sia solo version|Elastic Heart]]", which was originally a collaboration with [[The Weeknd]] and [[Diplo]], was released in January 2015.

To promote the project, Sia appears on a number of TV shows including ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'' and ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', where she recruited [[Maddie Ziegler]] as her persona onstage, during 2014 and 2015. ''1000 Forms of Fear'' earned Sia three [[ARIA Music Awards]] in [[ARIA Music Awards of 2014|2014]] and was listed as one of the best albums of 2014 by several publications including ''[[The Boston Globe]]'' and ''[[Rolling Stone]]''. The lead single "Chandelier" received four [[Grammy Award|Grammy]] nominations for [[Grammy Award for Song of the Year|Song of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Record of the Year|Record of the Year]], [[Grammy Award for Best Pop Solo Performance|Best Pop Solo Performance]] and [[Grammy Award for Best Music Video|Best Music Video]]

==Background==
[[File:Sia performing photograph by Kris Krug.jpg|thumb|left|Sia performing in 2008]]

In 2010, Sia released her fifth studio album, ''[[We Are Born]]'', which peaked at number 2 on the [[ARIA Charts|ARIA Albums Chart]] and was certified gold by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]].<ref>Australian chart position and certification for ''We Are Born'':
*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia|title=Discography Sia|publisher=[[ARIA Charts]]|accessdate=16 February 2015}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.aria.com.au/pages/httpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aupageshttpwww.aria.com.aualbumaccreds2011.htm|title=Accreditations <U+2013> 2011 Albums|publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association|accessdate=16 February 2015}}</ref> Following the release of ''We Are Born'', Sia decided to retire from the career as a recording artist and established a career as a [[songwriter]]. She wrote the song "[[Titanium (song)|Titanium]]" for American singer [[Alicia Keys]], but it was later sent to [[David Guetta]], who included Sia's original [[demo (music)|demo]] vocals on the song and released it as a single in 2011.<ref name="NPRMusic"/> "Titanium" was a commercial success worldwide, peaking within the top five of record charts in the United States, Australia and numerous European regions.<ref>Chart positions for "Titanium":
*{{cite web|url=http://www.australian-charts.com/showitem.asp?interpret=David+Guetta+feat.+Sia&titel=Titanium&cat=s|title=David Guetta feat. Sia <U+2013> Titanium|publisher=ARIA Charts|accessdate=17 February 2015}}
*{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/300445/David+Guetta/chart?f=379|title=David Guetta <U+2013> Chart history: Hot 100|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> However, Sia was not pleased with the success of the single: "[...] I never even knew it was gonna happen, and I was really upset. Because I had just retired, I was trying to be a pop songwriter, not an artist."<ref name="NPRMusic">{{cite web|url=http://www.npr.org/2014/07/08/329500971/a-reluctant-star-sia-deals-with-fame-on-her-own-terms|title=A Reluctant Star, Sia Deals With Fame on Her Own|publisher=[[NPR Music]]|date=8 July 2014|first=Sam|last=Sanders|accessdate=17 February 2015}}</ref> From 2011 to 2013, Sia became well-known for writing songs for a large number of recording artists, including [[Beyonc<U+00E9>]], [[Flo Rida]] and [[Rihanna]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|title=How a Song Written by Sia Furler Became a Hit|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=21 April 2014|first=Steve|last=Knopper|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20141205003032/http://6thfloor.blogs.nytimes.com/2014/04/21/how-a-song-written-by-sia-furler-becomes-a-hit/?_php=true&_type=blogs&_r=0|archivedate=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref name="Billboard cover">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/5770521/sia-the-billboard-cover-story |title=Sia: The Billboard Cover Story |first=Phil |last=Gallo |work=Billboard |date=25 October 2013 |accessdate=23 May 2014}}</ref>

By September 2013, Sia was recording vocal tracks at her home studio with the hope of releasing a new album the following spring.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gigwise.com/news/84168/sia-confirms-release-of-fifth-studio-album-in-march-2014 |title=Sia confirms release of fifth studio album in March, 2014 |publisher=[[Gigwise]] |date=13 September 2013 |accessdate=10 July 2014}}</ref> Later that year, a team of [[RCA Records]] representatives including the label's CEO [[Peter Edge]] met with Sia to discuss a record deal. Eventually, the singer signed a contract that would stipulate she doesn't have to tour or do press appearances to promote the album.<ref name="Billboard cover"/> In an interview published by ''[[NME]]'' in February 2015, Sia revealed that ''1000 Forms of Fear'' was released as a contractual obligation: "Basically, I put this out to get out of my publishing deal. I was planning to be a pop song writer for other artists. But my publishing deal was as an artist so I had to put one more album out. I didn't want to get famous so I kept all the songs I wanted and had a lot of fun making it."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/various-artists/82961|title=Sia reveals early details of brand new album 'This Is Acting'|first=David|last=Renshaw|work=[[NME]]|date=17 February 2015|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>

==Composition==
''1000 Forms of Fear'' is primarily an [[electropop]] album, with influences of [[hip hop music|hip hop]] and [[reggae]].<ref name="AVClub"/> It opens with "[[Chandelier (Sia song)|Chandelier]]", an electropop song that features a reggae-influenced beat.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-listen-sia-new-song-eye-of-the-needle-20140602-story.html|title=Sia smiles through the pain in new song 'Eye of the Needle'|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|first=Mikael|last=Wood|date=2 June 2014|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20150210203155/http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-listen-sia-new-song-eye-of-the-needle-20140602-story.html|archivedate=10 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/mar/17/sia-chandelier|title=Sia <U+2013> Chandelier|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=17 March 2014|first=Michael|last=Cragg|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140714145650/http://www.theguardian.com/music/musicblog/2014/mar/17/sia-chandelier|archivedate=14 July 2014}}</ref> Lyrically, the track talks about "the glitter and fatigue of a party girl's life."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1724271/sia-chandelier-sounds-like-rihanna/|title=Sia's New YOLO Song 'Chandelier' Could Have Been Rihanna's Next Hit|publisher=[[MTV News]]|first=Brenna|last=Ehrlich|date=17 March 2014|accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref> The follow-up, "[[Big Girls Cry]]", was compared to [[Alanis Morissette]]'s "[[Hands Clean]]".<ref name="NYTimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2014/07/08/arts/music/notable-releases-from-sia-and-mary-sarah.html?_r=0|title=Hitting the Ceiling, then Moving Up|work=The New York Times|date=8 July 2014|first=Jon|last=Pareles|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> On "Burn the Pages", Sia described a friend she wants to cheer up: "You're twisted up like a slipknot / Tied by a juicehead who just took his T-shot."<ref name="Slant"/> "[[Eye of the Needle (song)|Eye of the Needle]]" is a "military-march" [[piano ballad]],<ref name="Spin"/> while "Hostage" is a [[new wave music|new wave]] [[pop music|pop]] and [[ska music|ska]] track that features Sia's voice "cracking like a [[punk rock|punk]] singer."<ref name="AVClub"/><ref name="Observer"/> The sixth song, "Straight for the Knife," is [[musical instrument|instrumented]] by [[string instrument|string]]s and lyrically details a tempestuous relationship: "But will someone find me swinging from the rafters / I<U+2019>m hanging on your every word."<ref name="AVClub"/><ref name="NYTimes"/>

"Fair Game", where Sia sings "Watch me squirm baby, but you<U+2019>re just what I need,"<ref name="NYTimes"/> is a minimalist and string-laden song about the desire to find an equal partner.<ref name="AVClub"/> The solo version of "[[Elastic Heart#Sia solo version|Elastic Heart]]", which originally featured [[The Weeknd]] and [[Diplo]], is a [[trap music|trap]] song.<ref name="RS"/> The song addresses "the overwhelming strength [Sia] needed to convince herself that life was worth living after coming out of a crushing relationship."<ref name="Fact">{{cite web|url=http://www.factmag.com/2014/07/16/1000-forms-of-fear/|title=1000 Forms of Fear <U+2013> FACT magazine|work=[[Fact (UK magazine)|Fact]]|date=16 July 2014|first=Aimee|last=Cliff|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> "Free the Animal" lyrically "imagines being killed in lurid, masochistic detail" with the lyrics "Detonate me / Shoot me like a cannon ball / Granulate me / Kill me like an animal."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/blogs/nme-blogs/how-sias-personal-resurrection-became-her-greatest-work-yet|title=How Sia's Personal Resurrection Became Her Greatest Work Yet|first=Lucy|last=Jones|work=[[NME]]|date=17 July 2014|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> The tenth song, "Fire Meet Gasoline," was compared to [[Beyonc<U+00E9>]]'s "[[Halo (Beyonc<U+00E9> song)|Halo]]" by Harriet Gibsone from ''[[The Guardian]]''.<ref name="Guardian"/> "Cellophane" is an electropop track,<ref name="Telegraph"/> where Sia likened her self to "a basket filled with pain."<ref name="LATimes">{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/music/posts/la-et-ms-sia-1000-forms-of-fear-review-20140709-story.html|title=Sia keeps the pain alive on '1000 Forms of Fear'|first=Mikael|last=Wood|work=Los Angeles Times|date=9 July 2014|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> ''1000 Forms of Fear'' concluded with "Dressed in Black," which Heather Phares of [[AllMusic]] described as a ballad "with more depth than the ones she writes for hire."<ref name="AllMusic"/>

==Singles==
{{Listen
|filename=Sia - Chandelier.ogg
|title="Chandelier"
|description="Chandelier", a [[reggae]]-influenced [[electropop]] song, served as the album's [[lead single]]
|format=[[Ogg]]
|pos=left}}
"Chandelier" served as ''1000 Forms of Fear''{{'}}s [[lead single]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6084942/sia-1000-forms-of-fear-release-date-track-list-chandelier|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|title=Sia Announces '1000 Forms of Fear' Release Date & Track List|date=14 May 2014|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> It was released for [[music download|digital download]] onto the [[iTunes Store]]s on 17 March 2014.<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140501140928/https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/chandelier-single/id838293746|url=https://itunes.apple.com/us/album/chandelier-single/id838293746|title=Chandelier <U+2013> Single|publisher=[[iTunes Store]] ([[Apple Inc]])|location=United States|archivedate=1 May 2014}}</ref> A music video for the song was released on 6 May 2014;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/05/10/sia-chandelier-music-video_n_5298152.html|title=Sia's 'Chandelier' Music Video Is Hauntingly Beautiful|work=[[The Huffington Post]]|date=10 May 2014|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> it features dancer [[Maddie Ziegler]] in a blonde wig.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/pop-shop/6077552/sia-chandelier-video-dance-moms-maddie-ziegler|title=Sia Taps 'Dance Moms' Star For 'Chandelier' Video: Watch|work=Billboard|date=6 May 2014|accessdate=19 February 2015|first=Jason|last=Lipshutz}}</ref> The single became a commercial success, peaking at number 8 on the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]], becoming the first single by Sia to appear on the chart as a lead artist.<ref name="hot100">{{cite web | url=http://www.billboard.com/artist/279248/Sia/chart?f=379|title=Sia <U+2013> Chart history|work=Billboard|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> "Chandelier" also peaked within the top five of [[record chart]]s in Europe and Oceania countries, including: Flanders and France (number one), Australia and Norway (number two), New Zealand (number three), United Kingdom (number six), and Slovakia (number five).<ref name="nz">{{cite web|url=http://charts.org.nz/showinterpret.asp?interpret=Sia|title=Discography Sia|publisher=Charts.org.nz. Hung Medien|accessdate=30 December 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theofficialcharts.com/archive-chart/_/1/2014-07-12/|title=Archive Chart|publisher=[[UK Singles Chart]]|accessdate=19 February 2015}}</ref> The track was [[List of music recording certifications|certified]] triple platinum by the [[Australian Recording Industry Association]] and gold by [[Recorded Music NZ]].<ref name="ARIA2014">{{cite web|url=http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/singles|archiveurl=http://web.archive.org/web/20140620182619/http://www.ariacharts.com.au/chart/singles|title=ARIA Singles Chart: 16/6/2014|publisher=Australian Recording Industry Association|archivedate= 20 June 2014}}</ref><ref name="RMNZ">{{cite web|url=http://nztop40.co.nz/chart/singles?chart=2532|title=NZ Top 40 Singles Chart (7 July 2014)|publisher=Recorded Music NZ|accessdate=6 June 2014}}</ref>

"Eye of the Needle" was released digitally on 3 June 2014,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://nl-be.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/eye-of-the-needle/|title=Eye of the Needle (2014)|publisher=[[7digital]]|location=Belgium|language=Dutch|accessdate=20 January 2015}}</ref> while "Big Girls Cry" was made available for music download on 25 June.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://fi.7digital.com/artist/sia/release/big-girls-cry/|title=Big Girls Cry (2014)|publisher=7digital|date=20 January 2015|location=Finland}}</ref> "Elastic Heart" was released as the fourth single from ''1000 Forms of Fear'' in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radioairplay.fm/RadioDate/PublicDetails/102808/SIA-Elastic-Heart-RCA|title=SIA <U+2013> Elastic Heart (RCA)|publisher=Radio Airplay SRL|accessdate=9 January 2015|first=Claudia|last=Attanasi|language=Italian}}</ref> A music video for the song was released on 7 January 2015 and features Ziegler and actor [[Shia LaBeouf]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.usmagazine.com/entertainment/news/sias-elastic-heart-music-video-shia-labeouf-underwear-201571|title=Sia's 'Elastic Heart' Music Video Features Shia LaBeouf in Underwear, Dance Moms' Maddie Ziegler: Watch Now!|first=Rachel|last=McRady|work=[[US Weekly]]|date=7 January 2015|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref> "Elastic Heart" peaked at number 17 on the US ''Billboard'' Hot 100 and charted within the top five charts of several countries, including Australia and Ireland.<ref name="hot100"/><ref name="nz"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2015&year=2015&week=6|title=GFK Chart-Track|publisher=[[Irish Singles Chart]]|accessdate=9 January 2015}}</ref>

==Promotion==
{{quote box|width=30em|quote=I already have a much larger concept for this album and for how I'm going to present it and that was: I don't want to be famous. If [[Amy Winehouse]] was a [[Beehive (hairstyle)|beehive]] then I guess I'm a blonde [[Bob cut|bob]]. I thought 'well if that's my brand, how can I avoid having to use my face to sell something', so my intention was to create a blonde bob brand. Throughout this whole thing I'll put a different person in a blonde bob and either they lip-synch while I'm doing a live performance or they perform a dance or do some sort of performance while I have my back to the audience, as with ''Ellen''.|source=<U+2014> Sia<ref name="Dazed"/>}}
In an interview with ''[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed & Confused]]'', Sia explained that she had decided not to show her face in videos and press shots in the campaign for ''1000 Forms of Fear''; instead, she focused on creating visual art through her videos.<ref name="Dazed">{{cite web|url=http://www.dazeddigital.com/music/article/19982/1/sia-on-taking-performance-art-to-the-masses |title=Sia on taking performance to the masses |first=Michael |last=Cragg |work=[[Dazed & Confused (magazine)|Dazed]] |date=May 2014 |accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref> During the promotion of the album, Sia recruited Ziegler to be her persona on stage and performed with her back facing to the camera.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dailytelegraph.com.au/entertainment/sydney-confidential/shame-sia-for-using-maddie-as-a-decoy/story-fni0cvc9-1227219209181|title=Shame Sia, for using Maddie Ziegler as a decoy|work=[[The Daily Telegraph (Australia)|The Daily Telegraph]]|location=Australia|first=Annette|last=Sharp|date=13 February 2015|accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref> On 19 May 2014, Sia performed "Chandelier" on ''[[The Ellen DeGeneres Show]]'', where Maddie Ziegler recreated the choreography in the music video.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pitchfork.com/news/55254-sia-performs-chandelier-on-ellen/|title=Sia Performs 'Chandelier' on Ellen|publisher=Pitchfork Media|first=Jeremy|last=Gordon|date=19 May 2014|accessdate=7 June 2014}}</ref> Sia also performed the song on ''[[Late Night with Seth Meyers]]'' on 9 June 2014, with ''[[Girls (TV series)|Girls]]'' star [[Lena Dunham]] performing the choreography.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://time.com/2851658/lena-dunham-sia-chandelier-late-night-with-seth-meyers/|title=Watch Lena Dunham Dance To Sia's 'Chandelier' on Late Night with Seth Meyers|first=Megan|last=Gibson|date=10 June 2014|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]}}</ref> On 4 July 2014, Sia made an appearance on ''[[Jimmy Kimmel Live!]]'', where she performed "Chandelier", "Big Girls Cry" and "Elastic Heart".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mtv.com/news/1861328/sia-continues-to-hide-her-face-during-jimmy-kimmel-performance/|title=Sia Continues To Hide Her Face During <U+2018>Jimmy Kimmel<U+2019> Performance|first=Nadeska|last=Alexis|publisher=MTV News|date=4 July 2014|accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref>

On 30 July 2014, Sia performed "Chandelier", "Elastic Heart" and Big Girls Cry" on the [[VH1]]'s show "SoundClash".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vh1.com/music/tuner/2014-07-29/soundclash-leaked-set-list-ep-2/|title= Ed Sheeran, Grouplove + Sia's Set List for Episode 2 Leaked!|publisher=[[VH1]]|date=29 July 2014|accessdate=17 August 2014|first=Diane|last=Cho}}</ref> On 17 June 2015, Sia performed "Chandelier" and "Elastic Heart" on ''[[Saturday Night Live]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.villagevoice.com/music/2015/01/sia-snl-review.php|title=You Don't Have to 'Get' Sia to Love Her on 'SNL'
|date=18 January 2015|first=Hilary|last=Hughes|work=[[The Village Voice]]|accessdate=20 February 2015}}</ref> On 8 February 2015, Sia and Ziegler together with actress [[Kristen Wiig]] performed "Chandelier" in a room reminiscent of the video set on the [[2015 Grammy Awards]] telecast.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slate.com/blogs/browbeat/2015/02/08/kristen_wiig_dances_to_sia_s_chandelier_on_the_grammys_video.html|title=Watch Kristen Wiig Perform 'Chandelier' With Sia on the Grammys|work=[[Slate (magazine)|Slate]]|date=8 February 2015|accessdate=14 February 2015}}</ref>

